history.content:
Unfortunately, I don't know your answer about how cal central works.  The documentation from campus is very spotty.

Yes, switching a discussion for a waitlisted class bumps you to the back of the lecture waitlist.

For your first question, you should try waiting a day, to see if you're added in when the waitlist next processes. If you're not enrolled after a while, then it seems possible that this rumor may be true.

---

Edit: OP from above. I emailed the SIS folks about this. They said that because I dropped the second class, the auto waitlist engine will not generate a time conflict error message when it runs (about twice a day); 189 is full, but I'm guessing I'll be processed if and when people drop.

For your first question, you should try waiting a day, to see if you're added in when the waitlist next processes. If you're not enrolled after a while, then it seems possible that this rumor may be true.

children.subject: @OP, did dropping the conflicting classes and waiting to be processed as people drop, work for you? I'm planning on doing the same thing. Thanks!

history.content:
I've been 7th on the waitlist for 189 for a while, and I realized I wasn't getting off the waitlist because my discussion section conflicted with another class I was already enrolled in. (I'm not sure how I got to the state with a conflict, but I'm now trying to fix it).

I've dropped the second class, so 189 shouldn't conflict with anything now, but I've heard that Cal Central won't realize that I've cleared the conflict, and my only option is to re-enroll in 189. Is this true? Or will I be processed off the waitlist? I really don't want to lose my spot and risk not getting into the class.

Also, just for future reference, does switching a discussion for a waitlisted class bump you to the back of the waitlist? 

Thanks!
history.subject: Fixed a time conflict. Will I be added from the waitlist now?
